name: storagetransfer
title: Google Storage Transfer API
description: Transfers data from external data sources to a Google Cloud Storage bucket or between Google Cloud Storage buckets.

parameters.name: fields
parameters.desc: Selector specifying which fields to include in a partial response.

parameters.name: oauth_token
parameters.desc: OAuth 2.0 token for the current user.

parameters.name: quotaUser
parameters.desc: Available to use for quota purposes for server-side applications. Can be any arbitrary string assigned to a user, but should not exceed 40 characters.

parameters.name: key
parameters.desc: API key. Your API key identifies your project and provides you with API access, quota, and reports. Required unless you provide an OAuth 2.0 token.

parameters.name: prettyPrint
parameters.desc: Returns response with indentations and line breaks.

schemas.name: AwsS3Data
schemas.desc: An AwsS3Data can be a data source, but not a data sink. In an AwsS3Data, an object's name is the S3 object's key name.

fields.name: bucketName
fields.desc: S3 Bucket name (see [Creating a bucket](http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/dev/create-bucket-get-location-example.html)). Required.

fields.name: awsAccessKey
fields.desc: AWS access key used to sign the API requests to the AWS S3 bucket. Permissions on the bucket must be granted to the access ID of the AWS access key. Required.

schemas.name: ObjectConditions
schemas.desc: Conditions that determine which objects will be transferred.

fields.name: minTimeElapsedSinceLastModification
fields.desc: If unspecified, `minTimeElapsedSinceLastModification` takes a zero value and `maxTimeElapsedSinceLastModification` takes the maximum possible value of Duration. Objects that satisfy the object conditions must either have a `lastModificationTime` greater or equal to `NOW` - `maxTimeElapsedSinceLastModification` and less than `NOW` - `minTimeElapsedSinceLastModification`, or not have a `lastModificationTime`.

fields.name: maxTimeElapsedSinceLastModification
fields.desc: `maxTimeElapsedSinceLastModification` is the complement to `minTimeElapsedSinceLastModification`.

fields.name: includePrefixes
fields.desc: If `includePrefixes` is specified, objects that satisfy the object conditions must have names that start with one of the `includePrefixes` and that do not start with any of the `excludePrefixes`. If `includePrefixes` is not specified, all objects except those that have names starting with one of the `excludePrefixes` must satisfy the object conditions. Requirements: * Each include-prefix and exclude-prefix can contain any sequence of Unicode characters, of max length 1024 bytes when UTF8-encoded, and must not contain Carriage Return or Line Feed characters. Wildcard matching and regular expression matching are not supported. * None of the include-prefix or the exclude-prefix values can be empty, if specified. * Each include-prefix must include a distinct portion of the object namespace, i.e., no include-prefix may be a prefix of another include-prefix. * Each exclude-prefix must exclude a distinct portion of the object namespace, i.e., no exclude-prefix may be a prefix of another exclude-prefix. * If `includePrefixes` is specified, then each exclude-prefix must start with the value of a path explicitly included by `includePrefixes`. The max size of `includePrefixes` is 20.

fields.name: excludePrefixes
fields.desc: `excludePrefixes` must follow the requirements described for `includePrefixes`. The max size of `excludePrefixes` is 20.

schemas.name: ListOperationsResponse

fields.name: operations

schemas.name: ErrorLogEntry

fields.name: errorDetails
fields.desc: A list of messages that carry the error details.

schemas.name: AwsAccessKey
schemas.desc: AWS access key (see [AWS Security Credentials](http://docs.aws.amazon.com/general/latest/gr/aws-security-credentials.html)).

fields.name: accessKeyId
fields.desc: AWS access key ID. Required.

fields.name: secretAccessKey
fields.desc: AWS secret access key. This field is not returned in RPC responses. Required.

schemas.name: Date
schemas.desc: Represents a whole calendar date, e.g. date of birth. The time of day and time zone are either specified elsewhere or are not significant. The date is relative to the Proleptic Gregorian Calendar. The day may be 0 to represent a year and month where the day is not significant, e.g. credit card expiration date. The year may be 0 to represent a month and day independent of year, e.g. anniversary date. Related types are [google.type.TimeOfDay][google.type.TimeOfDay] and `google.protobuf.Timestamp`.

fields.name: year
fields.desc: Year of date. Must be from 1 to 9,999, or 0 if specifying a date without a year.

fields.name: month
fields.desc: Month of year of date. Must be from 1 to 12.

fields.name: day
fields.desc: Day of month. Must be from 1 to 31 and valid for the year and month, or 0 if specifying a year/month where the day is not sigificant.

For instance: service Foo { rpc Bar(google.protobuf.Empty) returns (google.protobuf.Empty); } The JSON representation for `Empty` is empty JSON object `{}`.

fields.name: objectsFromSourceFailed

fields.name: bytesFromSourceFailed

fields.name: objectsFailedToDeleteFromSink

fields.name: objectsFromSourceSkippedBySync
fields.desc: Objects in the data source that are not transferred because they already exist in the data sink.

fields.name: bytesFromSourceSkippedBySync
fields.desc: Bytes in the data source that are not transferred because they already exist in the data sink.

fields.name: objectsDeletedFromSource
fields.desc: Objects that are deleted from the data source.

fields.name: bytesDeletedFromSink
fields.desc: Bytes that are deleted from the data sink.

fields.name: bytesFoundFromSource
fields.desc: Bytes found in the data source that are scheduled to be transferred, which will be copied, excluded based on conditions, or skipped due to failures.

fields.name: objectsFoundOnlyFromSink
fields.desc: Objects found only in the data sink that are scheduled to be deleted.

fields.name: bytesFoundOnlyFromSink
fields.desc: Bytes found only in the data sink that are scheduled to be deleted.

fields.name: objectsDeletedFromSink

schemas.desc: Request passed to ResumeTransferOperation.

schemas.name: TransferJob
schemas.desc: This resource represents the configuration of a transfer job that runs periodically.

fields.name: description
fields.desc: A description provided by the user for the job. Its max length is 1024 bytes when Unicode-encoded.

fields.name: status
fields.desc: Status of the job. This value MUST be specified for `CreateTransferJobRequests`. NOTE: The effect of the new job status takes place during a subsequent job run. For example, if you change the job status from `ENABLED` to `DISABLED`, and an operation spawned by the transfer is running, the status change would not affect the current operation.

fields.name: deletionTime
fields.desc: This field cannot be changed by user requests.

fields.name: name
fields.desc: A globally unique name assigned by Storage Transfer Service when the job is created. This field should be left empty in requests to create a new transfer job; otherwise, the requests result in an `INVALID_ARGUMENT` error.

fields.name: projectId
fields.desc: The ID of the Google Developers Console project that owns the job. Required.

fields.name: transferSpec
fields.desc: Transfer specification. Required.

fields.name: schedule
fields.desc: Schedule specification. Required.

fields.name: creationTime
fields.desc: This field cannot be changed by user requests.

fields.name: lastModificationTime
fields.desc: This field cannot be changed by user requests.

schemas.name: GcsData
schemas.desc: In a GcsData, an object's name is the Google Cloud Storage object's name and its `lastModificationTime` refers to the object's updated time, which changes when the content or the metadata of the object is updated.

fields.name: bucketName
fields.desc: Google Cloud Storage bucket name (see [Bucket Name Requirements](https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/bucket-naming#requirements)). Required.

schemas.name: HttpData
schemas.desc: An HttpData specifies a list of objects on the web to be transferred over HTTP. The information of the objects to be transferred is contained in a file referenced by a URL. The first line in the file must be "TsvHttpData-1.0", which specifies the format of the file. Subsequent lines specify the information of the list of objects, one object per list entry. Each entry has the following tab-delimited fields: * HTTP URL * Length * MD5 - This field is a base64-encoded MD5 hash of the object An HTTP URL that points to the object to be transferred. It must be a valid URL with URL scheme HTTP or HTTPS. When an object with URL `http(s)://hostname:port/` is transferred to the data sink, the name of the object at the data sink is `/`. Length and MD5 provide the size and the base64-encoded MD5 hash of the object. If Length does not match the actual length of the object fetched, the object will not be transferred. If MD5 does not match the MD5 computed from the transferred bytes, the object transfer will fail. `lastModificationTime` is not available in HttpData objects. The objects that the URL list points to must allow public access. Storage Transfer Service obeys `robots.txt` rules and requires the HTTP server to support Range requests and to return a Content-Length header in each response.

fields.name: listUrl
fields.desc: The URL that points to the file that stores the object list entries. This file must allow public access. Currently, only URLs with HTTP and HTTPS schemes are supported. Required.

schemas.name: TransferOptions
schemas.desc: TransferOptions uses three boolean parameters to define the actions to be performed on objects in a transfer.

fields.name: overwriteObjectsAlreadyExistingInSink
fields.desc: Whether overwriting objects that already exist in the sink is allowed.

fields.name: deleteObjectsUniqueInSink
fields.desc: Whether objects that exist only in the sink should be deleted.

fields.name: deleteObjectsFromSourceAfterTransfer
fields.desc: Whether objects should be deleted from the source after they are transferred to the sink.

schemas.name: TimeOfDay
schemas.desc: Represents a time of day. The date and time zone are either not significant or are specified elsewhere. An API may chose to allow leap seconds. Related types are [google.type.Date][google.type.Date] and `google.protobuf.Timestamp`.

fields.name: minutes
fields.desc: Minutes of hour of day. Must be from 0 to 59.

fields.name: seconds
fields.desc: Seconds of minutes of the time. Must normally be from 0 to 59. An API may allow the value 60 if it allows leap-seconds.

fields.name: nanos
fields.desc: Fractions of seconds in nanoseconds. Must be from 0 to 999,999,999.

fields.name: hours
fields.desc: Hours of day in 24 hour format. Should be from 0 to 23. An API may choose to allow the value "24:00:00" for scenarios like business closing time.

schemas.name: UpdateTransferJobRequest
schemas.desc: Request passed to UpdateTransferJob.

fields.name: updateTransferJobFieldMask
fields.desc: The field mask of the fields in `transferJob` that are to be updated in this request. Fields in `transferJob` that can be updated are: `description`, `transferSpec`, and `status`. To update the `transferSpec` of the job, a complete transfer specification has to be provided. An incomplete specification which misses any required fields will be rejected with the error `INVALID_ARGUMENT`.

fields.name: projectId
fields.desc: The ID of the Google Developers Console project that owns the job. Required.

fields.name: transferJob
fields.desc: The job to update. Required.

schemas.name: Status
schemas.desc: The `Status` type defines a logical error model that is suitable for different programming environments, including REST APIs and RPC APIs. It is used by [gRPC](https://github.com/grpc). The error model is designed to be: - Simple to use and understand for most users - Flexible enough to meet unexpected needs # Overview The `Status` message contains three pieces of data: error code, error message, and error details. The error code should be an enum value of [google.rpc.Code][google.rpc.Code], but it may accept additional error codes if needed. The error message should be a developer-facing English message that helps developers *understand* and *resolve* the error. If a localized user-facing error message is needed, put the localized message in the error details or localize it in the client. The optional error details may contain arbitrary information about the error. There is a predefined set of error detail types in the package `google.rpc` which can be used for common error conditions. # Language mapping The `Status` message is the logical representation of the error model, but it is not necessarily the actual wire format. When the `Status` message is exposed in different client libraries and different wire protocols, it can be mapped differently. For example, it will likely be mapped to some exceptions in Java, but more likely mapped to some error codes in C. # Other uses The error model and the `Status` message can be used in a variety of environments, either with or without APIs, to provide a consistent developer experience across different environments. Example uses of this error model include: - Partial errors. If a service needs to return partial errors to the client, it may embed the `Status` in the normal response to indicate the partial errors. - Workflow errors. A typical workflow has multiple steps. Each step may have a `Status` message for error reporting purpose. - Batch operations. If a client uses batch request and batch response, the `Status` message should be used directly inside batch response, one for each error sub-response. - Asynchronous operations. If an API call embeds asynchronous operation results in its response, the status of those operations should be represented directly using the `Status` message. - Logging. If some API errors are stored in logs, the message `Status` could be used directly after any stripping needed for security/privacy reasons.

fields.name: code
fields.desc: The status code, which should be an enum value of [google.rpc.Code][google.rpc.Code].

fields.name: message
fields.desc: A developer-facing error message, which should be in English. Any user-facing error message should be localized and sent in the [google.rpc.Status.details][google.rpc.Status.details] field, or localized by the client.

fields.name: details
fields.desc: A list of messages that carry the error details. There will be a common set of message types for APIs to use.

schemas.name: ErrorSummary
schemas.desc: A summary of errors by error code, plus a count and sample error log entries.

fields.name: errorCount
fields.desc: Count of this type of error. Required.

fields.name: errorLogEntries
fields.desc: Error samples.

fields.name: errorCode
fields.desc: Required.

schemas.desc: Google service account

fields.name: accountEmail
fields.desc: Required.

schemas.name: TransferSpec
schemas.desc: Configuration for running a transfer.

fields.name: httpDataSource
fields.desc: An HTTP URL data source.

fields.name: gcsDataSink
fields.desc: A Google Cloud Storage data sink.

fields.name: objectConditions
fields.desc: Only objects that satisfy these object conditions are included in the set of data source and data sink objects. Object conditions based on objects' `lastModificationTime` do not exclude objects in a data sink.

fields.name: transferOptions
fields.desc: If the option `deleteObjectsUniqueInSink` is `true`, object conditions based on objects' `lastModificationTime` are ignored and do not exclude objects in a data source or a data sink.

fields.name: gcsDataSource
fields.desc: A Google Cloud Storage data source.

fields.name: awsS3DataSource
fields.desc: An AWS S3 data source.

schemas.name: Schedule
schemas.desc: Transfers can be scheduled to recur or to run just once.

fields.name: scheduleStartDate
fields.desc: The first day the recurring transfer is scheduled to run. Required.

fields.name: scheduleEndDate
fields.desc: The last day the recurring transfer will be run. If `scheduleEndDate` is the same as `scheduleStartDate`, the transfer will be executed only once.

fields.name: startTimeOfDay
fields.desc: The time in UTC at which the transfer will be scheduled to start in a day. Transfers may start later than this time. If not specified, transfers are scheduled to start at midnight UTC.

schemas.name: Operation
schemas.desc: This resource represents a long-running operation that is the result of a network API call.

fields.name: name
fields.desc: The server-assigned name, which is only unique within the same service that originally returns it. If you use the default HTTP mapping above, the `name` should have the format of `operations/some/unique/name`.

fields.name: metadata
fields.desc: Represents the transfer operation object.

fields.name: done
fields.desc: If the value is `false`, it means the operation is still in progress. If true, the operation is completed and the `result` is available.

fields.name: error
fields.desc: The error result of the operation in case of failure.

fields.name: response
fields.desc: The normal response of the operation in case of success. If the original method returns no data on success, such as `Delete`, the response is `google.protobuf.Empty`. If the original method is standard `Get`/`Create`/`Update`, the response should be the resource. For other methods, the response should have the type `XxxResponse`, where `Xxx` is the original method name. For example, if the original method name is `TakeSnapshot()`, the inferred response type is `TakeSnapshotResponse`.

schemas.name: TransferOperation
schemas.desc: A description of the execution of a transfer.

fields.name: projectId
fields.desc: The ID of the Google Developers Console project that owns the operation. Required.

fields.name: transferSpec
fields.desc: Transfer specification. Required.

fields.name: endTime
fields.desc: End time of this transfer execution.

fields.name: status
fields.desc: Status of the transfer operation.

fields.name: counters
fields.desc: Information about the progress of the transfer operation.

fields.name: errorBreakdowns
fields.desc: Summarizes errors encountered with sample error log entries.

fields.name: name
fields.desc: A globally unique ID assigned by the system.

fields.name: startTime
fields.desc: Start time of this transfer execution.

fields.name: transferJobName
fields.desc: The name of the transfer job that triggers this transfer operation.

methods.name: get
methods.desc: Returns the Google service account that is used by Storage Transfer Service to access buckets in the project where transfers run or in other projects. Each Google service account is associated with one Google Developers Console project. Users should add this service account to the Google Cloud Storage bucket ACLs to grant access to Storage Transfer Service. This service account is created and owned by Storage Transfer Service and can only be used by Storage Transfer Service.

pathParams.name: projectId
pathParams.desc: The ID of the Google Developers Console project that the Google service account is associated with. Required.

methods.name: getGoogleServiceAccount
methods.desc: Returns the Google service account that is used by Storage Transfer Service to access buckets in the project where transfers run or in other projects. Each Google service account is associated with one Google Developers Console project. Users should add this service account to the Google Cloud Storage bucket ACLs to grant access to Storage Transfer Service. This service account is created and owned by Storage Transfer Service and can only be used by Storage Transfer Service.

optinalQueryParams.name: projectId
optinalQueryParams.desc: The ID of the Google Developers Console project that the Google service account is associated with. Required.

optinalQueryParams.name: projectId
optinalQueryParams.desc: The ID of the Google Developers Console project that owns the job. Required.

optinalQueryParams.name: filter
optinalQueryParams.desc: A list of query parameters specified as JSON text in the form of {"`project_id`":"my_project_id", "`job_names`":["jobid1","jobid2",...], "`job_statuses`":["status1","status2",...]}. Since `job_names` and `job_statuses` support multiple values, their values must be specified with array notation. `project_id` is required. `job_names` and `job_statuses` are optional. The valid values for `job_statuses` are case-insensitive: `ENABLED`, `DISABLED`, and `DELETED`.

optinalQueryParams.name: pageSize
optinalQueryParams.desc: The list page size. The max allowed value is 256.

methods.name: create
methods.desc: Creates a transfer job that runs periodically.

methods.name: patch
methods.desc: Updates a transfer job. Updating a job's transfer spec does not affect transfer operations that are running already. Updating the scheduling of a job is not allowed.

pathParams.name: jobName
pathParams.desc: The name of job to update. Required.

pathParams.name: name
pathParams.desc: The name of the transfer operation. Required.

methods.name: resume
methods.desc: Resumes a transfer operation that is paused.

pathParams.name: name
pathParams.desc: The name of the transfer operation. Required.

methods.name: get
methods.desc: Gets the latest state of a long-running operation. Clients can use this method to poll the operation result at intervals as recommended by the API service.

pathParams.name: name
pathParams.desc: The name of the operation resource.

methods.name: list
methods.desc: Lists operations that match the specified filter in the request. If the server doesn't support this method, it returns `UNIMPLEMENTED`. NOTE: the `name` binding below allows API services to override the binding to use different resource name schemes, such as `users/*/operations`.

methods.name: cancel
methods.desc: Cancels a transfer. Use the get method to check whether the cancellation succeeded or whether the operation completed despite cancellation.

pathParams.name: name
pathParams.desc: The name of the operation resource to be cancelled.

methods.name: delete
methods.desc: This method is not supported and the server returns `UNIMPLEMENTED`.

pathParams.name: name
pathParams.desc: The name of the operation resource to be deleted.
